const SEC_JAVA = {
  id:"java",title:"Core Java",icon:"☕",ib:"rgba(56,189,248,.13)",ic:"#38bdf8",
  grp:"java",bar:"#38bdf8",tglow:"rgba(56,189,248,.07)",
  desc:"OOP, JVM internals, Collections, Streams, Generics, and Java 17/21 features.",
  tags:["OOP","JVM","Streams","Generics","Java 17","Collections"],
  qs:[
    {q:"What is the difference between JDK, JRE, and JVM?",d:"easy",
     a:"<strong>JDK</strong> (Java Development Kit) bundles the compiler (<code>javac</code>), debugger, JavaDoc, and the JRE — everything needed to develop and run Java programs.<br><br><strong>JRE</strong> (Java Runtime Environment) contains the standard class libraries and the JVM — enough to <em>run</em> Java programs but not compile them.<br><br><strong>JVM</strong> (Java Virtual Machine) is the engine that loads bytecode, JIT-compiles hot methods to native machine code, and manages memory (GC). It is platform-specific; the bytecode is platform-neutral.<br><br>Relationship: <code>JDK ⊃ JRE ⊃ JVM</code>."},

    {q:"What are the four pillars of OOP and how does Java implement each?",d:"easy",
     a:"<strong>Encapsulation:</strong> Bundle data (fields) and behaviour (methods) in a class. Mark fields <code>private</code>; expose via public getters/setters. Protects internal state.<br><br><strong>Inheritance:</strong> A subclass acquires fields and methods of its parent via <code>extends</code>. Java supports single-class inheritance. Promotes code reuse.<br><br><strong>Polymorphism:</strong> One interface, many implementations. <em>Compile-time</em> — method overloading (same name, different parameters). <em>Runtime</em> — method overriding + dynamic dispatch (JVM calls the subclass version at runtime).<br><br><strong>Abstraction:</strong> Hide implementation details behind a contract. Achieved with <code>abstract</code> classes (partial implementation) and <code>interface</code>s (pure contract). Callers depend on the abstraction, not the concrete class."},

    {q:"What is the difference between == and .equals() in Java?",d:"easy",
     a:"<code>==</code> compares <strong>references</strong> — it asks \"do these two variables point to the exact same object in memory?\"<br><br><code>.equals()</code> compares <strong>logical content</strong> — defined by the class author to express value equality.<br><br><pre>String a = new String(\"hello\");\nString b = new String(\"hello\");\na == b        // false  (different objects)\na.equals(b)   // true   (same characters)</pre><br>String literals share the String Pool so <code>\"hello\" == \"hello\"</code> is true — but never rely on this. Always use <code>.equals()</code> for strings.<br><br><strong>Contract:</strong> whenever you override <code>equals()</code> you <em>must</em> also override <code>hashCode()</code> so that equal objects produce the same hash — required by <code>HashMap</code> and <code>HashSet</code>."},

    {q:"Explain the Java Memory Model — heap, stack, and metaspace.",d:"medium",
     a:"<strong>Stack</strong> (per-thread): LIFO structure storing primitive local variables, method call frames, and object <em>references</em>. Fast allocation/deallocation via stack pointer. Stack overflow → <code>StackOverflowError</code> (usually deep recursion).<br><br><strong>Heap</strong> (shared): all object instances live here. Divided into:<ul><li><em>Young Gen</em> — Eden + 2 Survivor spaces. Most objects die young (minor GC).</li><li><em>Old Gen</em> — long-lived objects promoted from Young Gen (major/full GC).</li></ul><br><strong>Metaspace</strong> (Java 8+, replaced PermGen): class metadata — bytecode, method signatures, constant pool. Lives in <em>native memory</em>, grows dynamically (no fixed size ⇒ no more <code>OutOfMemoryError: PermGen</code>). Tune with <code>-XX:MaxMetaspaceSize</code>."},

    {q:"How does HashMap work internally in Java 8+?",d:"hard",
     a:"<code>HashMap</code> uses an <strong>array of buckets</strong> (default 16).<br><br><strong>put(key, value):</strong><ol><li>Compute <code>hash = key.hashCode()</code>; spread bits via internal hash function.</li><li><code>index = hash & (capacity-1)</code> — find bucket.</li><li>If empty, insert <code>Node(key, value, hash, next=null)</code>.</li><li>If collision, compare <code>hash</code> and <code>equals()</code>: match → update; no match → append to chain.</li></ol><br><strong>Java 8 treeification:</strong> when a bucket chain length &gt; 8 <em>and</em> table size ≥ 64, the linked list converts to a Red-Black tree → O(log n) worst-case instead of O(n).<br><br><strong>Resize:</strong> when <code>size &gt; capacity × loadFactor</code> (default 0.75), capacity doubles and all entries are rehashed. Expensive — pre-size with <code>new HashMap&lt;&gt;(expectedSize / 0.75 + 1)</code>."},

    {q:"What is the difference between String, StringBuilder, and StringBuffer?",d:"easy",
     a:"<strong>String:</strong> <em>immutable</em>. Every concatenation (<code>+</code>, <code>concat()</code>) creates a new object. JVM may optimise compile-time constants. The String Pool caches literals.<br><br><strong>StringBuilder:</strong> <em>mutable</em>, not thread-safe. <code>append()</code> is O(1) amortised. Use in single-threaded code — loops, builders.<br><br><strong>StringBuffer:</strong> <em>mutable</em>, <em>thread-safe</em> (all methods are <code>synchronized</code>). Slower than StringBuilder due to locking. Only use when multiple threads genuinely share the buffer (rare).<br><br>For single-threaded string building always use <code>StringBuilder</code>."},

    {q:"What are generics and what is type erasure?",d:"medium",
     a:"Generics provide <strong>compile-time type safety</strong> for collections, methods, and classes. <code>List&lt;String&gt;</code> prevents accidentally adding an <code>Integer</code> — caught at compile time, no cast needed on retrieval.<br><br><strong>Type erasure:</strong> the compiler removes all generic type parameters at compile time, replacing them with their upper bounds (usually <code>Object</code>). At runtime, <code>List&lt;String&gt;</code> and <code>List&lt;Integer&gt;</code> are both just <code>List</code>.<br><br><strong>Consequences of erasure:</strong><ul><li>Cannot do <code>new T()</code> or <code>new T[n]</code></li><li>Cannot do <code>instanceof List&lt;String&gt;</code></li><li>Cannot overload on generic type alone</li></ul><br>Use bounded wildcards: <code>&lt;? extends Number&gt;</code> (covariant read) and <code>&lt;? super Integer&gt;</code> (contravariant write) — PECS principle."},

    {q:"What is the difference between an abstract class and an interface (Java 8+)?",d:"medium",
     a:"<table><tr><td></td><td><strong>Abstract class</strong></td><td><strong>Interface</strong></td></tr><tr><td>Instance fields</td><td>✅ Yes</td><td>❌ No (only constants)</td></tr><tr><td>Constructors</td><td>✅ Yes</td><td>❌ No</td></tr><tr><td>Concrete methods</td><td>✅ Yes</td><td>✅ <code>default</code> / <code>static</code> (Java 8+)</td></tr><tr><td>Multiple inheritance</td><td>❌ One parent only</td><td>✅ Implement many</td></tr><tr><td>Access modifiers</td><td>Any</td><td>Public/package by default</td></tr></table><br><strong>Rule of thumb:</strong> use an <em>interface</em> to define a capability contract (<code>Serializable</code>, <code>Runnable</code>); use an <em>abstract class</em> when subclasses share common state, a constructor, or a partial implementation (Template Method pattern)."},

    {q:"What are functional interfaces and how do lambdas relate to them?",d:"medium",
     a:"A <strong>functional interface</strong> has exactly one abstract method (SAM — Single Abstract Method). Examples: <code>Runnable</code>, <code>Callable&lt;V&gt;</code>, <code>Comparator&lt;T&gt;</code>, <code>Predicate&lt;T&gt;</code>, <code>Function&lt;T,R&gt;</code>, <code>Supplier&lt;T&gt;</code>, <code>Consumer&lt;T&gt;</code>.<br><br><code>@FunctionalInterface</code> is optional but makes the compiler enforce the SAM constraint — good practice.<br><br><strong>Lambdas</strong> are concise anonymous implementations of functional interfaces:<br><pre>// Old\nComparator&lt;String&gt; c = new Comparator&lt;String&gt;() {\n  public int compare(String a, String b) { return a.compareTo(b); }\n};\n// Lambda\nComparator&lt;String&gt; c = (a, b) -&gt; a.compareTo(b);\n// Method reference\nComparator&lt;String&gt; c = String::compareTo;</pre>"},

    {q:"Explain Java 8 Streams — lazy evaluation and the intermediate vs terminal distinction.",d:"medium",
     a:"A Stream is a declarative pipeline of operations over a data source (collection, array, I/O, infinite generator).<br><br><strong>Intermediate operations</strong> are <em>lazy</em> — they return a new Stream and nothing executes yet: <code>filter()</code>, <code>map()</code>, <code>flatMap()</code>, <code>distinct()</code>, <code>sorted()</code>, <code>peek()</code>, <code>limit()</code>, <code>skip()</code>.<br><br><strong>Terminal operations</strong> <em>trigger</em> the pipeline: <code>collect()</code>, <code>forEach()</code>, <code>reduce()</code>, <code>count()</code>, <code>findFirst()</code>, <code>anyMatch()</code>, <code>toList()</code> (Java 16).<br><br><strong>Short-circuiting:</strong> <code>findFirst()</code> stops after the first match — without lazy evaluation you'd process every element. This makes infinite streams like <code>Stream.iterate(0, n-&gt;n+1)</code> practical.<br><br><strong>Parallel streams:</strong> <code>list.parallelStream()</code> splits work across ForkJoinPool threads — only beneficial for CPU-heavy, stateless operations on large datasets."},

    {q:"What is Optional and when should you NOT use it?",d:"medium",
     a:"<code>Optional&lt;T&gt;</code> is a container that explicitly models the potential absence of a value — a better alternative to returning <code>null</code>.<br><br><strong>Key API:</strong> <code>of()</code>, <code>ofNullable()</code>, <code>empty()</code>, <code>isPresent()</code>, <code>get()</code>, <code>orElse(default)</code>, <code>orElseGet(supplier)</code>, <code>orElseThrow()</code>, <code>map(fn)</code>, <code>flatMap(fn)</code>, <code>ifPresent(consumer)</code>.<br><br><strong>Do NOT use Optional as:</strong><ul><li>Method parameters — use overloads instead</li><li>Collection elements — use an empty collection</li><li>Serialized fields — Jackson/JSON issues, extra weight</li><li>Performance-critical hot paths — object allocation overhead</li></ul><br>Best used as a <em>return type</em> for methods that may genuinely not produce a value."},

    {q:"How does garbage collection work? Explain G1GC vs ZGC.",d:"hard",
     a:"JVM uses <strong>generational GC</strong> based on the observation that most objects die young.<br><br><strong>G1GC</strong> (default since Java 9): divides the heap into equal-sized regions (~1–32 MB). Tracks \"liveness\" per region and collects the regions with most garbage first (Garbage-First). Targets a configurable pause-time goal (<code>-XX:MaxGCPauseMillis=200</code>). Concurrent marking phase runs alongside the application. Suitable for heaps 4 GB–100 GB.<br><br><strong>ZGC</strong> (production-ready Java 15+): performs almost all work concurrently with the application using load barriers. Achieves sub-millisecond pauses even on multi-terabyte heaps. Does not require a pause-time tuning parameter. Use ZGC for latency-sensitive services on very large heaps.<br><br><strong>Shenandoah</strong> (OpenJDK): similar concurrent approach to ZGC, available in some distributions."},

    {q:"What are Java records and sealed classes (Java 16–17)?",d:"medium",
     a:"<strong>Records</strong> (stable Java 16): immutable data carriers. The compiler auto-generates canonical constructor, accessors (no get prefix), <code>equals()</code>, <code>hashCode()</code>, <code>toString()</code>.<br><pre>record Point(int x, int y) {}\nPoint p = new Point(3, 4);\np.x(); // 3</pre>Custom compact constructor for validation: <code>Point { if (x &lt; 0) throw new IllegalArgumentException(); }</code><br><br><strong>Sealed classes</strong> (stable Java 17): restrict which classes can extend/implement a type.<br><pre>sealed interface Shape permits Circle, Rectangle, Triangle {}</pre>Enables <em>exhaustive pattern matching</em> in switch expressions — compiler knows all subtypes so no default case needed. Together they form a powerful algebraic data type system."},

    {q:"What is the difference between Comparable and Comparator?",d:"medium",
     a:"<code>Comparable&lt;T&gt;</code>: implemented <em>inside</em> the class. Defines the <strong>natural ordering</strong>. <code>int compareTo(T other)</code>. Used by <code>Collections.sort()</code>, <code>TreeSet</code>, <code>TreeMap</code> by default.<br><br><code>Comparator&lt;T&gt;</code>: external comparison strategy. Use when you don't own the class, need a different ordering, or need multiple orderings.<br><pre>// Multi-field comparator (Java 8+)\nComparator&lt;Person&gt; cmp = Comparator\n  .comparing(Person::getAge)\n  .thenComparing(Person::getName)\n  .reversed();\n\nlist.sort(cmp);</pre><br><code>Comparator.naturalOrder()</code> and <code>Comparator.reverseOrder()</code> are utility comparators for natural ordering. <code>Comparator.nullsFirst/nullsLast()</code> safely handles nulls."},

    {q:"What is the difference between HashMap, LinkedHashMap, and TreeMap?",d:"medium",
     a:"<strong>HashMap:</strong> O(1) avg get/put/remove. <em>No ordering guarantee</em>. Best choice for pure key-value lookup.<br><br><strong>LinkedHashMap:</strong> O(1) operations. Maintains <em>insertion order</em> (default) or <em>access order</em> (constructor flag). The access-order variant implements an LRU cache when combined with <code>removeEldestEntry()</code>.<br><br><strong>TreeMap:</strong> O(log n) all operations. Keys kept in <em>sorted order</em> (natural or Comparator). Supports range views: <code>subMap(from, to)</code>, <code>headMap(to)</code>, <code>floorKey(k)</code>, <code>ceilingKey(k)</code>. Backed by a Red-Black tree. Use when you need ordered iteration or range queries."},

    {q:"What are WeakReference, SoftReference, and PhantomReference?",d:"hard",
     a:"Java has four reference strengths (strongest to weakest):<br><br><strong>Strong (normal):</strong> object never GC'd while reachable.<br><br><strong>SoftReference:</strong> collected only when JVM is under memory pressure. Ideal for memory-sensitive caches — entries survive as long as heap is available.<br><br><strong>WeakReference:</strong> collected at the <em>next</em> GC cycle regardless of heap size. Used in <code>WeakHashMap</code> — entries auto-evict when the key has no other strong reference.<br><br><strong>PhantomReference:</strong> enqueued to a <code>ReferenceQueue</code> <em>after</em> the object is finalized but before memory is reclaimed. Use for post-mortem cleanup (replacing deprecated <code>finalize()</code>). Java 9+ <code>Cleaner</code> is the preferred API.<br><br>All three can be combined with a <code>ReferenceQueue</code> to receive notification when the object is collected."},

    {q:"What is the difference between checked and unchecked exceptions?",d:"medium",
     a:"<strong>Checked exceptions</strong> extend <code>Exception</code> but not <code>RuntimeException</code>. The compiler forces you to either <code>catch</code> them or declare them with <code>throws</code>. Examples: <code>IOException</code>, <code>SQLException</code>, <code>ParseException</code>.<br><br><strong>Unchecked exceptions</strong> extend <code>RuntimeException</code> (or <code>Error</code>). No declaration required. Examples: <code>NullPointerException</code>, <code>IllegalArgumentException</code>, <code>IndexOutOfBoundsException</code>.<br><br><strong>When to use each:</strong> checked for <em>recoverable</em> external conditions (file not found, network error — caller can react meaningfully); unchecked for <em>programming errors</em> or unrecoverable conditions. Modern Java and frameworks (Spring) strongly prefer unchecked to avoid cluttered method signatures and forced catch blocks that swallow exceptions."},

    {q:"What are virtual threads (Java 21) and how do they change backend development?",d:"hard",
     a:"<strong>Virtual threads</strong> (Project Loom, stable Java 21) are JVM-managed, lightweight threads — not mapped 1:1 to OS threads. The JVM scheduler multiplexes millions of virtual threads onto a small pool of OS carrier threads.<br><br><strong>Key behaviour:</strong> when a virtual thread blocks on I/O (JDBC, HTTP, file read), the carrier OS thread is <em>immediately released</em> and picks up another virtual thread — no OS thread wastage.<br><br><strong>Impact on backend:</strong> the classic scaling bottleneck (thread-per-request blocking I/O) disappears <em>without</em> reactive programming complexity. Spring Boot 3.2+: enable with <code>spring.threads.virtual.enabled=true</code>.<br><br><strong>Caveats:</strong> CPU-bound tasks still need OS threads; <code>synchronized</code> blocks can pin the carrier thread — replace with <code>ReentrantLock</code>; thread locals work but pools of virtual threads shouldn't share state."},

    {q:"What is the String Pool and how does string interning work?",d:"medium",
     a:"The <strong>String Pool</strong> (part of the heap since Java 7) is a cache of unique <code>String</code> instances. When you write a string literal (<code>\"hello\"</code>), the JVM checks the pool: if the value exists, it returns the existing reference; otherwise it creates a new entry.<br><br><code>new String(\"hello\")</code> always creates a new heap object, <em>bypassing</em> the pool.<br><br><code>String.intern()</code> manually places a String in the pool and returns the canonical reference:<br><pre>String a = new String(\"hello\");\nString b = a.intern();\nb == \"hello\" // true — same pooled instance</pre><br><strong>Practical use:</strong> interning is useful when you store millions of repeated string values (e.g., enum-like strings from a database) to reduce heap pressure. The pool is garbage-collected in modern JVMs so unused interned strings are freed."},

    {q:"Explain method hiding vs method overriding in Java.",d:"hard",
     a:"<strong>Method overriding</strong> applies to <em>instance methods</em>. When a subclass defines an instance method with the same signature, the JVM calls the subclass version based on the <em>runtime type</em> of the object — this is dynamic dispatch / polymorphism.<br><br><strong>Method hiding</strong> applies to <em>static methods</em>. When a subclass defines a static method with the same signature, the version called depends on the <em>reference type</em> at compile time, not the runtime type.<br><pre>Animal a = new Dog();\na.speak();         // Dog.speak() — overriding (runtime type)\na.staticMethod();  // Animal.staticMethod() — hiding (compile-time type)</pre><br><strong>Private methods</strong> are not overridden — each class has its own private copy. <code>@Override</code> on a private method in a subclass creates a new unrelated method (no annotation error but also no polymorphism)."}
  ]
};

SEC_JAVA.qs.push(
  {q:"What is the difference between Runnable and Callable?",d:"easy",
   a:"<strong>Runnable:</strong> functional interface with <code>void run()</code> — cannot return a value or throw checked exceptions. Used with <code>Thread</code> or <code>ExecutorService.submit()</code>.<br><br><strong>Callable&lt;V&gt;:</strong> functional interface with <code>V call() throws Exception</code> — can return a value and throw checked exceptions. Used with <code>ExecutorService.submit()</code> which returns a <code>Future&lt;V&gt;</code>.<br><pre>Future&lt;Integer&gt; f = executor.submit(() -&gt; {\n  return computeExpensiveValue();\n});\nint result = f.get(); // blocks until done</pre><br>Use Runnable for fire-and-forget tasks; Callable when you need the result or need to propagate checked exceptions."},

  {q:"What is the difference between final, finally, and finalize()?",d:"easy",
   a:"Three completely unrelated keywords that often appear together in interviews:<br><br><strong>final:</strong> keyword with three uses:<ul><li><code>final int x = 5</code> — variable cannot be reassigned</li><li><code>final class String</code> — class cannot be extended</li><li><code>final void method()</code> — method cannot be overridden in subclasses</li></ul><br><strong>finally:</strong> block in try-catch-finally. Always executes after try/catch — even if an exception was thrown. Used to release resources (though try-with-resources is now preferred).<br><pre>try { conn.execute(); }\ncatch (Exception e) { log.error(e); }\nfinally { conn.close(); } // always runs</pre><br><strong>finalize():</strong> method called by the GC before collecting an object. Deprecated since Java 9, removed in Java 18. Unreliable and problematic. Use <code>Cleaner</code> or try-with-resources instead."},

  {q:"What is the difference between an Iterator and a ListIterator?",d:"medium",
   a:"<strong>Iterator:</strong> can traverse any <code>Collection</code> (not just lists). Supports forward-only traversal. Methods: <code>hasNext()</code>, <code>next()</code>, <code>remove()</code> (optional).<br><br><strong>ListIterator:</strong> extends Iterator, only works with <code>List</code> implementations. Adds bidirectional traversal and modification:<ul><li><code>hasPrevious()</code>, <code>previous()</code> — traverse backwards</li><li><code>add(e)</code> — insert element at current position</li><li><code>set(e)</code> — replace last returned element</li><li><code>nextIndex()</code>, <code>previousIndex()</code> — get current position</li></ul><br>Use Iterator for general collection traversal; ListIterator when you need to traverse backwards or modify a list while iterating."},

  {q:"What is covariance and contravariance in Java generics?",d:"hard",
   a:"<strong>Covariance (<code>&lt;? extends T&gt;</code> — upper bounded wildcard):</strong> accept T or any subtype. Can <em>read</em> from the structure but not write (except null).<br><pre>List&lt;? extends Number&gt; nums = new ArrayList&lt;Integer&gt;();\nNumber n = nums.get(0); // OK\nnums.add(42); // COMPILE ERROR</pre><br><strong>Contravariance (<code>&lt;? super T&gt;</code> — lower bounded wildcard):</strong> accept T or any supertype. Can <em>write</em> T into the structure but reading gives Object.<br><pre>List&lt;? super Integer&gt; list = new ArrayList&lt;Number&gt;();\nlist.add(42); // OK\nObject o = list.get(0); // only Object</pre><br><strong>PECS principle</strong> (Producer Extends, Consumer Super):<ul><li>If you're reading FROM the collection (producer) → use <code>extends</code></li><li>If you're writing INTO the collection (consumer) → use <code>super</code></li></ul>Example: <code>Collections.copy(List&lt;? super T&gt; dest, List&lt;? extends T&gt; src)</code>"},

  {q:"What is the difference between deep copy and shallow copy?",d:"medium",
   a:"<strong>Shallow copy:</strong> creates a new object with copied field values. For reference-type fields, copies the reference — both original and copy point to the same nested objects.<br><pre>class Order {\n  List&lt;Item&gt; items; // reference field\n}\nOrder copy = new Order();\ncopy.items = original.items; // same list!\ncopy.items.add(newItem);     // modifies original too!</pre><br><strong>Deep copy:</strong> recursively copies all nested objects — fully independent copy.<br><pre>Order deepCopy = new Order();\ndeepCopy.items = new ArrayList&lt;&gt;(original.items); // new list\n// For mutable items, copy each item too</pre><br><strong>Java mechanisms for deep copy:</strong><ul><li>Manual — implement copy constructors or factory methods</li><li>Serialization — serialize to bytes, deserialize to new object (slow)</li><li>Cloneable + override <code>clone()</code> (error-prone, avoid)</li><li>Library — ModelMapper, MapStruct, Jackson (serialize/deserialize)</li></ul><br>Prefer explicit copy constructors or builders over <code>Cloneable</code>."},

  {q:"What are sealed interfaces and pattern matching for switch in Java 21?",d:"hard",
   a:"<strong>Sealed interfaces</strong> restrict which classes can implement them — you control the complete hierarchy:<br><pre>sealed interface Shape permits Circle, Rectangle, Triangle {}\nrecord Circle(double radius) implements Shape {}\nrecord Rectangle(double w, double h) implements Shape {}\nrecord Triangle(double base, double h) implements Shape {}</pre><br><strong>Pattern matching for switch</strong> (stable Java 21) uses sealed types for exhaustive switching:<br><pre>double area = switch (shape) {\n  case Circle c    -&gt; Math.PI * c.radius() * c.radius();\n  case Rectangle r -&gt; r.w() * r.h();\n  case Triangle t  -&gt; 0.5 * t.base() * t.h();\n  // NO default needed — compiler knows all subtypes\n};</pre><br><strong>Guarded patterns:</strong><br><pre>case Circle c when c.radius() &gt; 100 -&gt; \"large circle\";\ncase Circle c -&gt; \"small circle\";</pre><br>This enables functional-style algebraic data types in Java — a type-safe alternative to instanceof chains and class hierarchies."}
);

SEC_JAVA.qs.push(
  {q:"What is pattern matching for instanceof (Java 16+)?",d:"easy",
   a:"Before Java 16, checking and casting required two steps:<br><pre>// Old way\nif (obj instanceof String) {\n  String s = (String) obj; // redundant cast\n  System.out.println(s.length());\n}</pre><br><strong>Pattern matching</strong> combines the check and binding into one expression:<br><pre>// Java 16+\nif (obj instanceof String s) {\n  System.out.println(s.length()); // s is already String\n}\n\n// Works with negation too\nif (!(obj instanceof String s)) {\n  throw new IllegalArgumentException();\n}\n// s is in scope here too!</pre><br><strong>In switch expressions (Java 21):</strong><br><pre>String result = switch (obj) {\n  case Integer i -> \"int: \" + i;\n  case String s  -> \"str: \" + s;\n  case null      -> \"null\";\n  default        -> \"other\";\n};</pre><br>Eliminates entire classes of ClassCastException and makes code significantly more readable."},

  {q:"What are text blocks in Java 15+?",d:"easy",
   a:"Text blocks provide a cleaner syntax for multi-line string literals — no more <code>\\n</code>, no more string concatenation for JSON/SQL/HTML.<br><br><pre>// Old way — messy\nString json = \"{\\n\" +\n  \"  \\\"name\\\": \\\"Alice\\\",\\n\" +\n  \"  \\\"age\\\": 30\\n\" +\n\"}\";\n\n// Text block\nString json = \"\"\"\n    {\n      \"name\": \"Alice\",\n      \"age\": 30\n    }\n    \"\"\";</pre><br><strong>Rules:</strong><ul><li>Opening <code>\"\"\"</code> must be followed by a newline</li><li>Closing <code>\"\"\"</code> position determines indentation stripping — common leading whitespace is removed</li><li>Trailing newline is included unless closing <code>\"\"\"</code> is on same line as last content</li></ul><br><strong>Useful for:</strong> SQL queries, JSON payloads in tests, HTML templates, GraphQL queries. Works seamlessly with <code>String.formatted()</code>:<br><pre>String query = \"\"\"\n    SELECT * FROM users\n    WHERE id = %d\n    \"\"\".formatted(userId);</pre>"},

  {q:"What is var (local variable type inference) in Java 10+?",d:"easy",
   a:"<code>var</code> lets the compiler infer the type of a local variable from its initializer — reducing boilerplate without losing static typing.<br><br><pre>// Without var\nMap&lt;String, List&lt;Order&gt;&gt; ordersByCustomer = new HashMap&lt;&gt;();\nBufferedReader reader = new BufferedReader(new FileReader(\"file.txt\"));\n\n// With var\nvar ordersByCustomer = new HashMap&lt;String, List&lt;Order&gt;&gt;();\nvar reader = new BufferedReader(new FileReader(\"file.txt\"));</pre><br><strong>Restrictions — var CANNOT be used for:</strong><ul><li>Method parameters or return types</li><li>Fields</li><li>Variables without an initializer: <code>var x;</code> — illegal</li><li>Lambda parameters (use explicit type or <code>_</code> in Java 21)</li><li><code>var x = null;</code> — compiler can't infer type from null</li></ul><br><strong>Best practice:</strong> use <code>var</code> when the type is obvious from the right-hand side (constructor, factory method). Avoid when it reduces clarity:<br><pre>var result = process(); // unclear — what type is result?\nvar list = new ArrayList&lt;String&gt;(); // clear</pre>"},

  {q:"How does try-with-resources work and what is AutoCloseable?",d:"medium",
   a:"Try-with-resources automatically closes resources declared in the <code>try()</code> header — guaranteeing <code>close()</code> is called even if an exception is thrown.<br><br><pre>// Old way — verbose and error-prone\nConnection conn = null;\ntry {\n  conn = dataSource.getConnection();\n  // use conn\n} finally {\n  if (conn != null) conn.close(); // easy to forget\n}\n\n// Try-with-resources\ntry (Connection conn = dataSource.getConnection();\n     PreparedStatement ps = conn.prepareStatement(sql)) {\n  // use conn and ps\n} // both closed automatically in reverse order</pre><br><strong>AutoCloseable:</strong> any class implementing <code>AutoCloseable</code> (one method: <code>void close() throws Exception</code>) can be used. <code>Closeable</code> extends it with <code>IOException</code>.<br><br><strong>Suppressed exceptions:</strong> if both the body and <code>close()</code> throw, the close exception is <em>suppressed</em> (attached to the primary exception via <code>getSuppressed()</code>) — the original exception is not lost.<br><br><strong>Java 9 enhancement:</strong> you can use effectively-final variables declared outside: <code>try (conn) { ... }</code>"},

  {q:"What are the different types of nested classes in Java?",d:"medium",
   a:"Java has four kinds of nested classes:<br><br><strong>Static nested class:</strong> declared <code>static</code> inside an outer class. No reference to the outer instance. Acts like a regular top-level class that's namespaced.<br><pre>class Outer {\n  static class StaticNested { ... } // no Outer.this\n}</pre><br><strong>Inner class (non-static):</strong> implicitly holds a reference to the enclosing outer instance. Can access outer's private members.<br><pre>class Outer {\n  class Inner { \n    void foo() { Outer.this.field; } // outer reference\n  }\n}</pre><br><strong>Local class:</strong> defined inside a method. Can access effectively-final locals.<br><br><strong>Anonymous class:</strong> unnamed class defined and instantiated in one expression. Common before lambdas.<br><pre>Runnable r = new Runnable() {\n  public void run() { ... }\n};</pre><br><strong>Memory leak risk:</strong> non-static inner classes and anonymous classes holding an outer reference prevent GC of the outer object. Prefer static nested classes unless you genuinely need the outer reference.<br><br><strong>Java 16+ records and interfaces</strong> can be declared static nested."},

  {q:"What is the Enum type and what can it do beyond simple constants?",d:"medium",
   a:"Enums in Java are full classes — each constant is a singleton instance of the enum class.<br><br><strong>Beyond simple constants — fields, methods, constructors:</strong><br><pre>public enum HttpStatus {\n  OK(200, \"OK\"),\n  NOT_FOUND(404, \"Not Found\"),\n  INTERNAL_ERROR(500, \"Internal Server Error\");\n\n  private final int code;\n  private final String reason;\n\n  HttpStatus(int code, String reason) {\n    this.code = code;\n    this.reason = reason;\n  }\n\n  public int getCode() { return code; }\n\n  public static HttpStatus fromCode(int code) {\n    return Arrays.stream(values())\n      .filter(s -&gt; s.code == code)\n      .findFirst()\n      .orElseThrow();\n  }\n}</pre><br><strong>Abstract methods per constant:</strong><br><pre>enum Operation {\n  ADD { public int apply(int a, int b) { return a + b; } },\n  MUL { public int apply(int a, int b) { return a * b; } };\n  public abstract int apply(int a, int b);\n}</pre><br><strong>EnumSet and EnumMap:</strong> highly efficient collections backed by bit vectors/arrays — much faster than HashSet/HashMap for enum keys."},

  {q:"What is String.format() vs String.formatted() vs MessageFormat?",d:"easy",
   a:"<strong>String.format(pattern, args):</strong> static method, C-style printf format specifiers.<br><pre>String s = String.format(\"Hello %s, you are %d years old\", name, age);\n// %s=string, %d=integer, %f=float, %.2f=2 decimal places\n// %n=platform newline, %t=date/time</pre><br><strong>String.formatted(args)</strong> (Java 15+): instance method on the format string — cleaner with text blocks:<br><pre>String msg = \"Hello %s, you have %d messages\".formatted(name, count);\n\n// Great with text blocks:\nString json = \"\"\"\n    {\"user\": \"%s\", \"age\": %d}\n    \"\"\".formatted(name, age);</pre><br><strong>MessageFormat:</strong> index-based placeholders, locale-aware, supports pluralization and date/number formatting:<br><pre>String msg = MessageFormat.format(\n  \"At {0,time} on {0,date}, {1} earned {2,number,currency}\",\n  new Date(), \"Alice\", 1000.50\n);</pre><br><strong>When to use each:</strong> <code>formatted()</code> for simple cases; <code>MessageFormat</code> for i18n/locale-sensitive output; structured logging frameworks (SLF4J <code>{}</code> placeholders) for log messages."},

  {q:"What is the difference between Iterator's remove() and Collection's remove()?",d:"medium",
   a:"Modifying a collection while iterating over it with a for-each loop throws <code>ConcurrentModificationException</code> (fail-fast iterators):<br><br><pre>// WRONG — throws ConcurrentModificationException\nfor (String s : list) {\n  if (s.startsWith(\"x\")) list.remove(s);\n}</pre><br><strong>Safe removal during iteration — Iterator.remove():</strong><br><pre>Iterator&lt;String&gt; it = list.iterator();\nwhile (it.hasNext()) {\n  if (it.next().startsWith(\"x\")) {\n    it.remove(); // removes last element returned by next()\n  }\n}</pre><br><strong>Java 8+ — removeIf() (cleanest):</strong><br><pre>list.removeIf(s -&gt; s.startsWith(\"x\"));</pre><br><strong>Key rules for Iterator.remove():</strong><ul><li>Must call <code>next()</code> before <code>remove()</code></li><li>Can only call <code>remove()</code> once per <code>next()</code> call</li><li>Not all iterators support remove (throws <code>UnsupportedOperationException</code> for unmodifiable collections)</li></ul>"},

  {q:"What are method references and what are the four kinds?",d:"medium",
   a:"Method references are a shorthand for lambdas that simply call an existing method. Syntax: <code>ClassName::methodName</code><br><br><strong>1. Static method reference:</strong><br><pre>// Lambda:  (x) -> Integer.parseInt(x)\n// Ref:     Integer::parseInt\nlist.stream().map(Integer::parseInt)</pre><br><strong>2. Instance method of a particular object:</strong><br><pre>// Lambda:  (x) -> myPrinter.print(x)\n// Ref:     myPrinter::print\nlist.forEach(myPrinter::print)</pre><br><strong>3. Instance method of an arbitrary object of a type:</strong><br><pre>// Lambda:  (s) -> s.toUpperCase()\n// Ref:     String::toUpperCase\nlist.stream().map(String::toUpperCase)</pre><br><strong>4. Constructor reference:</strong><br><pre>// Lambda:  (s) -> new StringBuilder(s)\n// Ref:     StringBuilder::new\nlist.stream().map(StringBuilder::new)</pre><br><strong>When to use:</strong> method references are more readable than lambdas when the lambda does nothing but delegate to a single method. If you need to transform arguments or combine calls, use a lambda instead."},

  {q:"What is the Collections utility class and its most important methods?",d:"easy",
   a:"<code>java.util.Collections</code> provides static utility methods for collection operations:<br><br><strong>Sorting & searching:</strong><br><pre>Collections.sort(list);                          // natural order\nCollections.sort(list, comparator);              // custom order\nCollections.binarySearch(sortedList, key);       // O(log n)\nCollections.reverse(list);\nCollections.shuffle(list);                       // random order\nCollections.swap(list, i, j);</pre><br><strong>Min/Max:</strong><br><pre>Collections.min(collection);\nCollections.max(collection, comparator);</pre><br><strong>Frequency & disjoint:</strong><br><pre>Collections.frequency(collection, element);      // count occurrences\nCollections.disjoint(c1, c2);                    // true if no common elements</pre><br><strong>Unmodifiable wrappers:</strong><br><pre>List&lt;String&gt; immutable = Collections.unmodifiableList(list);\n// throws UnsupportedOperationException on mutation\n\n// Java 9+ — prefer these (truly immutable):\nList.of(\"a\", \"b\");\nSet.of(\"x\", \"y\");\nMap.of(\"k\", \"v\");</pre><br><strong>Singleton/empty collections:</strong><br><pre>Collections.singletonList(\"only\"); // immutable single-element list\nCollections.emptyList();           // shared empty instance, no allocation</pre>"}
);

SEC_JAVA.qs.push(
  {q:"What is pattern matching for instanceof (Java 16+)?",d:"easy",
   a:"Before Java 16, checking and casting required two steps:<br><pre>if (obj instanceof String) {\n  String s = (String) obj; // redundant cast\n  System.out.println(s.length());\n}</pre><br><strong>Pattern matching (Java 16 stable):</strong> combines the check and binding into one expression:<br><pre>if (obj instanceof String s) {\n  System.out.println(s.length()); // s is String, in scope here\n}\n\n// Negation pattern\nif (!(obj instanceof String s)) {\n  return; // s not in scope here\n}\nSystem.out.println(s.length()); // s IS in scope here</pre><br><strong>With guards:</strong><br><pre>if (obj instanceof String s && s.length() > 5) {\n  System.out.println(\"long string: \" + s);\n}</pre><br><strong>In switch (Java 21):</strong><br><pre>String result = switch (obj) {\n  case Integer i -> \"int: \" + i;\n  case String s  -> \"str: \" + s;\n  case null      -> \"null\";\n  default        -> \"other\";\n};</pre>"},

  {q:"What are text blocks in Java 15+ and how do they work?",d:"easy",
   a:"Text blocks provide multi-line string literals without manual escape sequences. Delimited by <code>\"\"\"</code>.<br><br><pre>// Old way\nString json = \"{\\n  \\\"name\\\": \\\"Alice\\\",\\n  \\\"age\\\": 30\\n}\";\n\n// Text block\nString json = \"\"\"\n        {\n          \"name\": \"Alice\",\n          \"age\": 30\n        }\n        \"\"\";</pre><br><strong>Indentation handling:</strong> the closing <code>\"\"\"</code> position determines the common indent to strip. Content to the right of the closing delimiter is preserved.<br><br><strong>Escape sequences:</strong><ul><li><code>\\n</code> — still works</li><li><code>\\</code> at end of line — suppresses newline (join lines)</li><li><code>\\s</code> — explicit space (prevents trailing whitespace trimming)</li></ul><br><strong>Common uses:</strong> JSON/XML/HTML templates, SQL queries, test fixtures — anywhere you previously needed ugly string concatenation."},

  {q:"What is the var keyword (local variable type inference) in Java 10+?",d:"easy",
   a:"<code>var</code> lets the compiler infer the type of a local variable from the initialiser — reducing boilerplate without losing static typing.<br><pre>// Before\nMap&lt;String, List&lt;Integer&gt;&gt; map = new HashMap&lt;String, List&lt;Integer&gt;&gt;();\n\n// With var\nvar map = new HashMap&lt;String, List&lt;Integer&gt;&gt;();\nvar list = new ArrayList&lt;String&gt;();\nvar entry = map.entrySet().iterator().next();</pre><br><strong>Rules — var can only be used for:</strong><ul><li>Local variables with an initialiser</li><li>for-loop index variables</li><li>try-with-resources variables</li></ul><br><strong>Cannot use var for:</strong> method parameters, return types, fields, catch parameters, or variables without an initialiser (<code>var x;</code>).<br><br><strong>Type is still static:</strong> <code>var s = \"hello\"</code> — <code>s</code> is <code>String</code> at compile time, not <code>Object</code>. No dynamic typing.<br><br><strong>When to avoid:</strong> when the inferred type is not obvious from reading the right side — readability matters more than brevity."},

  {q:"What are nested classes in Java — static nested, inner, local, and anonymous?",d:"medium",
   a:"<strong>Static nested class:</strong> declared inside another class with <code>static</code>. Does NOT have access to instance members of the outer class. Used when the nested class logically belongs to the outer but doesn't need its state. E.g., <code>Map.Entry</code>, Builder classes.<br><pre>class Outer {\n  static class Builder { ... } // no Outer instance needed\n}</pre><br><strong>Inner class (non-static):</strong> has implicit reference to the enclosing outer instance. Can access all outer members including private. Risk: prevents GC of outer object (memory leak).<br><pre>class Outer {\n  class Inner { void foo() { outerField = 1; } } // access outer\n}</pre><br><strong>Local class:</strong> defined inside a method. Rarely used.<br><br><strong>Anonymous class:</strong> unnamed one-time implementation. Largely replaced by lambdas for functional interfaces, but still used for abstract classes with multiple methods:<br><pre>Comparator&lt;String&gt; c = new Comparator&lt;&gt;() {\n  public int compare(String a, String b) { return a.compareTo(b); }\n};</pre><br><strong>Rule:</strong> prefer static nested classes — inner classes create hidden outer references causing subtle memory leaks."},

  {q:"What is try-with-resources and how does it differ from finally?",d:"medium",
   a:"<code>try-with-resources</code> (Java 7+) automatically closes any <code>AutoCloseable</code> resource when the try block exits — even on exception.<br><pre>// Old way — easy to forget close or get exception order wrong\nConnection conn = null;\ntry {\n  conn = ds.getConnection();\n  // use conn\n} finally {\n  if (conn != null) conn.close(); // what if this throws too?\n}\n\n// try-with-resources\ntry (Connection conn = ds.getConnection();\n     PreparedStatement ps = conn.prepareStatement(sql)) {\n  // use conn and ps\n} // both auto-closed in reverse order, even on exception</pre><br><strong>Multiple resources:</strong> closed in reverse declaration order.<br><br><strong>Suppressed exceptions:</strong> if both the try block and <code>close()</code> throw, the close exception is suppressed (attached to the primary exception via <code>getSuppressed()</code>) — the original exception is not lost, unlike the <code>finally</code> approach where the finally exception swallows the original.<br><br><strong>Custom AutoCloseable:</strong><br><pre>class Timer implements AutoCloseable {\n  long start = System.nanoTime();\n  public void close() { log.info(\"elapsed: {}ms\", (System.nanoTime()-start)/1_000_000); }\n}</pre>"},

  {q:"How do Java enums work internally and what advanced features do they support?",d:"medium",
   a:"Enums are full classes that extend <code>java.lang.Enum</code>. Each constant is a singleton instance of the enum class — created once when the class is loaded.<br><br><strong>Built-in methods:</strong> <code>name()</code>, <code>ordinal()</code>, <code>valueOf(String)</code>, <code>values()</code>.<br><br><strong>Fields and methods:</strong><br><pre>enum Planet {\n  MERCURY(3.303e+23, 2.4397e6),\n  EARTH(5.976e+24, 6.37814e6);\n\n  private final double mass, radius;\n\n  Planet(double mass, double radius) {\n    this.mass = mass;\n    this.radius = radius;\n  }\n\n  double surfaceGravity() { return 6.67300E-11 * mass / (radius * radius); }\n}</pre><br><strong>Abstract methods per constant:</strong><br><pre>enum Operation {\n  ADD { public int apply(int a, int b) { return a + b; } },\n  MUL { public int apply(int a, int b) { return a * b; } };\n  public abstract int apply(int a, int b);\n}</pre><br><strong>EnumMap / EnumSet:</strong> extremely efficient — backed by an array indexed by ordinal. Always prefer over HashMap/HashSet when keys are enums."},

  {q:"What are the main methods of the Collections utility class?",d:"easy",
   a:"<code>java.util.Collections</code> provides static utility methods for collection operations:<br><br><strong>Sorting and searching:</strong><ul><li><code>sort(list)</code>, <code>sort(list, comparator)</code></li><li><code>binarySearch(list, key)</code> — list must be sorted first</li><li><code>reverse(list)</code>, <code>shuffle(list)</code></li><li><code>swap(list, i, j)</code>, <code>rotate(list, distance)</code></li></ul><br><strong>Min/Max:</strong><ul><li><code>min(collection)</code>, <code>max(collection)</code></li></ul><br><strong>Frequency and disjoint:</strong><ul><li><code>frequency(collection, obj)</code> — count occurrences</li><li><code>disjoint(c1, c2)</code> — true if no common elements</li></ul><br><strong>Wrappers:</strong><ul><li><code>unmodifiableList(list)</code> — read-only view (throws on mutation)</li><li><code>synchronizedList(list)</code> — thread-safe wrapper</li><li><code>singletonList(obj)</code>, <code>emptyList()</code>, <code>nCopies(n, obj)</code></li></ul><br><strong>Modern alternatives:</strong> <code>List.of()</code>, <code>List.copyOf()</code> (Java 9+) return truly immutable lists — prefer these over <code>Collections.unmodifiableList()</code>."},

  {q:"What is the difference between String.format(), formatted(), and MessageFormat?",d:"medium",
   a:"<strong>String.format(template, args):</strong> C-style printf formatting. Most common approach.<br><pre>String s = String.format(\"Hello %s, you are %d years old\", name, age);\n// Common format specifiers:\n// %s string, %d integer, %f float, %n newline\n// %.2f two decimal places, %10s right-pad to 10 chars</pre><br><strong>String.formatted(args)</strong> (Java 15+): instance method on a string literal — same as format but more readable:<br><pre>String s = \"Hello %s, age %d\".formatted(name, age);</pre><br><strong>MessageFormat:</strong> internationalisation-friendly, supports plurals and date/number formatting:<br><pre>String s = MessageFormat.format(\n  \"At {0,time} on {0,date}, there were {1,number} visitors.\",\n  new Date(), 1_234);</pre><br><strong>String.valueOf() vs toString():</strong> <code>valueOf(null)</code> returns <code>\"null\"</code>; <code>null.toString()</code> throws NPE — always use <code>valueOf</code> when the object might be null.<br><br><strong>Formatted strings in Java 21:</strong> string templates are in preview — <code>STR.\"Hello \\{name}\"</code>."},

);

SEC_JAVA.qs.push(
  {q:"What is pattern matching for instanceof (Java 16+)?",d:"medium",
   a:"Before Java 16, using <code>instanceof</code> required an explicit cast:<br><pre>if (obj instanceof String) {\n  String s = (String) obj; // redundant cast\n  System.out.println(s.length());\n}</pre><br><strong>Pattern matching (Java 16 stable):</strong> binds the cast result to a new variable in one step:<br><pre>if (obj instanceof String s) {\n  System.out.println(s.length()); // s is already String\n}</pre><br>The binding variable <code>s</code> is scoped to the branch where the condition is true — the compiler guarantees it's always a <code>String</code> there.<br><br><strong>With switch (Java 21 stable):</strong><br><pre>String describe(Object obj) {\n  return switch (obj) {\n    case Integer i  -> \"int: \" + i;\n    case String s   -> \"str: \" + s.toUpperCase();\n    case null       -> \"null\";\n    default         -> \"other: \" + obj.getClass().getSimpleName();\n  };\n}</pre><br>Eliminates long if-else instanceof chains. Compiler warns if a case is unreachable."},

  {q:"What are text blocks (Java 15+) and when should you use them?",d:"easy",
   a:"Text blocks are multi-line string literals that preserve formatting without explicit escape sequences. Introduced as stable in Java 15.<br><pre>// Old way — hard to read\nString json = \"{\\n  \\\"name\\\": \\\"Alice\\\",\\n  \\\"age\\\": 30\\n}\";\n\n// Text block\nString json = \"\"\"\n        {\n          \"name\": \"Alice\",\n          \"age\": 30\n        }\n        \"\"\";</pre><br><strong>Rules:</strong><ul><li>Opening <code>\"\"\"</code> must be followed by a newline</li><li>Closing <code>\"\"\"</code> controls indentation — common leading whitespace is stripped based on its column position</li><li>Trailing newline included unless closing <code>\"\"\"</code> is on the last content line</li></ul><br><strong>Best for:</strong> SQL queries, JSON/XML payloads in tests, HTML snippets, multi-line log messages. <code>String.formatted()</code> works with text blocks for interpolation."},

  {q:"What is var (local variable type inference) and what are its limitations?",d:"easy",
   a:"<code>var</code> (Java 10+) lets the compiler infer the type of a local variable from the right-hand side — reduces verbosity without losing static typing.<br><pre>// Before\nMap&lt;String, List&lt;Order&gt;&gt; ordersByUser = new HashMap&lt;&gt;();\n\n// With var\nvar ordersByUser = new HashMap&lt;String, List&lt;Order&gt;&gt;();</pre><br><strong>Limitations:</strong><ul><li>Only for <strong>local variables</strong> — not fields, method parameters, or return types</li><li>Must have an initialiser — <code>var x;</code> is illegal</li><li>Cannot initialise with <code>null</code> — type cannot be inferred</li><li>Cannot use with lambda expressions directly — <code>var fn = x -&gt; x + 1</code> is illegal</li></ul><br><strong>When to use:</strong> when the type is obvious from the right-hand side (constructor calls, factory methods). <strong>Avoid</strong> when the type is not immediately obvious — e.g., <code>var result = service.process(input)</code> hides what <code>result</code> actually is."},

  {q:"What are nested and inner classes in Java — static vs non-static?",d:"medium",
   a:"Java has four kinds of nested types:<br><br><strong>Static nested class:</strong> declared inside another class with <code>static</code>. Acts like a top-level class — no reference to the outer instance. Use for logically grouping helper classes:<br><pre>class Order {\n  static class Builder { ... } // no access to Order.this\n}</pre><br><strong>Inner class (non-static):</strong> holds an implicit reference to the enclosing instance. Can access outer class private members. Risk: prevents GC of outer instance if inner lives longer.<br><pre>class EventBus {\n  class Subscription {\n    void cancel() { EventBus.this.unsubscribe(this); }\n  }\n}</pre><br><strong>Local class:</strong> declared inside a method, can access effectively-final local variables.<br><br><strong>Anonymous class:</strong> one-time-use class for an interface or abstract class (largely replaced by lambdas).<br><br><strong>Best practice:</strong> prefer static nested classes unless you specifically need access to the outer instance — non-static inner classes are a common memory leak source."},

  {q:"What is try-with-resources and how does it work with multiple resources?",d:"medium",
   a:"try-with-resources (Java 7+) automatically closes resources that implement <code>AutoCloseable</code>, even if an exception is thrown — replacing verbose finally blocks.<br><pre>// Old way\nConnection conn = null;\ntry {\n  conn = dataSource.getConnection();\n  // use conn\n} finally {\n  if (conn != null) conn.close(); // what if close() also throws?\n}\n\n// try-with-resources\ntry (Connection conn = dataSource.getConnection()) {\n  // conn auto-closed on exit\n}</pre><br><strong>Multiple resources</strong> — closed in reverse order of declaration:<br><pre>try (\n  Connection conn = dataSource.getConnection();\n  PreparedStatement ps = conn.prepareStatement(sql);\n  ResultSet rs = ps.executeQuery()\n) {\n  // rs closed first, then ps, then conn\n}</pre><br><strong>Suppressed exceptions:</strong> if both the body and <code>close()</code> throw, the close exception is suppressed (accessible via <code>e.getSuppressed()</code>) and the body exception propagates — the opposite of a finally block."},

  {q:"How do Java enums work internally and what can they contain?",d:"medium",
   a:"Java enums are special classes — each constant is a <code>public static final</code> instance of the enum class. They cannot be instantiated or extended.<br><br><strong>Enums can contain:</strong><ul><li>Fields and constructors (constructor is always private)</li><li>Abstract methods — each constant provides its own implementation</li><li>Concrete methods</li><li>Interfaces (implements)</li></ul><br><pre>public enum Planet {\n  MERCURY(3.303e+23, 2.4397e6),\n  EARTH(5.976e+24, 6.37814e6);\n\n  private final double mass, radius;\n  Planet(double mass, double radius) {\n    this.mass = mass; this.radius = radius;\n  }\n  double surfaceGravity() { return 6.67300E-11 * mass / (radius * radius); }\n}</pre><br><strong>Enum utilities:</strong> <code>values()</code> returns all constants; <code>valueOf(\"EARTH\")</code> parses by name; <code>ordinal()</code> gives position (avoid using ordinal for persistence — use name or a dedicated field).<br><br><strong>EnumSet / EnumMap:</strong> bit-vector backed, extremely fast — use instead of HashSet/HashMap when keys are enum constants."},

  {q:"What is the Collections utility class — key methods every developer should know?",d:"easy",
   a:"<code>java.util.Collections</code> provides static utility methods for collections:<br><br><strong>Sorting and searching:</strong><br><pre>Collections.sort(list);                        // natural order\nCollections.sort(list, Comparator.reverseOrder());\nint idx = Collections.binarySearch(sortedList, key);\nCollections.reverse(list);\nCollections.shuffle(list);</pre><br><strong>Min/Max:</strong><br><pre>String min = Collections.min(list);\nString max = Collections.max(list, comparator);</pre><br><strong>Frequency and disjoint:</strong><br><pre>int count = Collections.frequency(list, \"apple\");\nboolean noOverlap = Collections.disjoint(list1, list2);</pre><br><strong>Unmodifiable views:</strong><br><pre>List&lt;String&gt; safe = Collections.unmodifiableList(list);\n// safe.add() throws UnsupportedOperationException</pre><br><strong>Singleton and empty collections:</strong><br><pre>List&lt;String&gt; one = Collections.singletonList(\"only\");\nList&lt;String&gt; empty = Collections.emptyList(); // prefer over new ArrayList&lt;&gt;()</pre><br><strong>Note:</strong> Java 9+ <code>List.of()</code>, <code>Set.of()</code>, <code>Map.of()</code> are the modern replacement for immutable collections."},

  {q:"What is the difference between String.format(), formatted(), and MessageFormat?",d:"easy",
   a:"<strong>String.format()</strong>: classic printf-style formatting. Returns a new String.<br><pre>String s = String.format(\"Hello %s, you are %d years old\", name, age);\nString money = String.format(\"%.2f\", 1234.5678); // \"1234.57\"</pre><br><strong>String.formatted()</strong> (Java 15+): instance method version — same as <code>String.format()</code> but called on the format string. Works great with text blocks:<br><pre>String msg = \"Order %s placed for %s\".formatted(orderId, customerName);\n\nString body = \"\"\"\n  Dear %s,\n  Your order %s is confirmed.\n  \"\"\".formatted(name, orderId);</pre><br><strong>MessageFormat:</strong> better for internationalisation — handles pluralisation and locale-aware formatting:<br><pre>String pattern = \"At {0,time} on {0,date}, there were {1,number} visitors.\";\nString result = MessageFormat.format(pattern, new Date(), 42);</pre><br><strong>Common format specifiers:</strong> <code>%s</code> (string), <code>%d</code> (integer), <code>%f</code> (float), <code>%n</code> (newline), <code>%b</code> (boolean), <code>%x</code> (hex), <code>%05d</code> (zero-padded)."},

  {q:"What are default methods in interfaces and what problem do they solve?",d:"medium",
   a:"Default methods (Java 8) allow interfaces to have concrete method implementations without breaking existing implementors — enabling API evolution.<br><br><strong>Problem they solve:</strong> before Java 8, adding a new method to an interface broke all existing implementations. With default methods, the interface provides a default implementation that subclasses can optionally override.<br><pre>interface Collection&lt;E&gt; {\n  // New in Java 8 — existing implementations get this for free\n  default Stream&lt;E&gt; stream() {\n    return StreamSupport.stream(spliterator(), false);\n  }\n\n  default void forEach(Consumer&lt;? super E&gt; action) {\n    for (E e : this) action.accept(e);\n  }\n}</pre><br><strong>Diamond problem resolution:</strong> if a class implements two interfaces with the same default method, it <em>must</em> override it to resolve ambiguity:<br><pre>class MyClass implements A, B {\n  public void hello() {\n    A.super.hello(); // explicitly choose which default\n  }\n}</pre><br><strong>Rule:</strong> class always wins over interface; more specific interface wins over less specific."},

  {q:"How does hashCode() contract work and what breaks it silently in a HashMap?",d:"hard",
   a:"The hashCode contract (from Object.hashCode() javadoc):<br><br><strong>1. Consistency:</strong> if <code>equals()</code> doesn't change, <code>hashCode()</code> must return the same value across multiple calls.<br><strong>2. Equality implies same hashCode:</strong> if <code>a.equals(b)</code>, then <code>a.hashCode() == b.hashCode()</code> MUST be true.<br><strong>3. Not required reverse:</strong> different objects can have the same hashCode (collisions are allowed).<br><br><strong>Silent breakage — mutable key:</strong><br><pre>class User {\n  String name;\n  @Override public int hashCode() { return name.hashCode(); }\n  @Override public boolean equals(Object o) { ... }\n}\n\nHashMap&lt;User, Order&gt; orders = new HashMap&lt;&gt;();\nUser user = new User(\"Alice\");\norders.put(user, order);\nuser.name = \"Bob\"; // MUTATION after insert\norders.get(user);  // returns null — user now hashes to wrong bucket!</pre><br><strong>Rule:</strong> never mutate fields used in <code>hashCode()</code>/<code>equals()</code> after inserting into a hash-based collection. Use immutable keys or only immutable fields (final, computed once)."},

  {q:"What is ClassLoader and how does parent delegation work?",d:"hard",
   a:"A ClassLoader loads <code>.class</code> files into the JVM. Java uses a hierarchy of ClassLoaders with <strong>parent delegation</strong> — before loading a class itself, a ClassLoader first asks its parent.<br><br><strong>Bootstrap ClassLoader (native C):</strong> loads core JDK classes from <code>rt.jar</code> or <code>java.base</code> module (String, Object, etc.).<br><br><strong>Extension/Platform ClassLoader:</strong> loads JDK extensions (<code>javax.*</code>, <code>java.sql.*</code>).<br><br><strong>Application ClassLoader:</strong> loads classes from the classpath (your app code, dependencies).<br><br><strong>Parent delegation flow:</strong><br><pre>1. Check if class is already loaded (findLoadedClass)\n2. Delegate to parent ClassLoader first\n3. If parent returns null, only then load it yourself</pre><br><strong>Why parent delegation?</strong> prevents a malicious <code>java.lang.String</code> on the classpath from replacing the JDK's String — the Bootstrap ClassLoader always wins.<br><br><strong>Custom ClassLoaders:</strong> web containers (Tomcat) use separate ClassLoaders per WAR for isolation. OSGi uses a custom non-delegating model for modularity."},

  {q:"What is the Integer cache and when does == on Integer return true?",d:"medium",
   a:"Java caches <code>Integer</code> objects for values in the range <code>-128 to +127</code> by default (via <code>Integer.valueOf()</code>). This means <code>==</code> will return <code>true</code> for cached values but <code>false</code> outside the range.<br><pre>Integer a = 100, b = 100;\nSystem.out.println(a == b);  // true (cached)\n\nInteger c = 200, d = 200;\nSystem.out.println(c == d);  // false (not cached, different objects)\n\nc.equals(d);  // true — always use .equals() for Integer comparison</pre><br><strong>Why the cache exists:</strong> small integers are used extremely frequently (loop counters, status codes) — caching reduces object allocation overhead.<br><br><strong>Cache range is configurable:</strong> <code>-XX:AutoBoxCacheMax=1000</code> extends the upper limit to 1000.<br><br><strong>Best practice:</strong> NEVER use <code>==</code> for <code>Integer</code>, <code>Long</code>, or any boxed primitive comparison in production code — always use <code>.equals()</code>. <code>==</code> checks reference identity, not value equality."},

  {q:"What is the difference between Serializable and Externalizable?",d:"hard",
   a:"Both allow objects to be converted to a byte stream (for file I/O, network, caching), but <code>Externalizable</code> gives you full control over the format.<br><br><strong>Serializable (automatic, declarative):</strong><br><pre>public class User implements Serializable {\n  private String name;\n  private transient String password; // excluded from serialization\n}</pre>The JVM uses reflection to serialize all non-transient fields. Override <code>writeObject()</code> and <code>readObject()</code> for custom behavior.<br><br><strong>Externalizable (manual, explicit):</strong><br><pre>public class User implements Externalizable {\n  private String name;\n  private String password;\n\n  @Override\n  public void writeExternal(ObjectOutput out) throws IOException {\n    out.writeUTF(name);\n    // password not written — manual control\n  }\n\n  @Override\n  public void readExternal(ObjectInput in) throws IOException {\n    name = in.readUTF();\n  }\n}</pre><br><strong>Key difference:</strong> Externalizable requires you to write every field explicitly — better performance (no reflection), smaller output, but more error-prone. <strong>Externalizable requires a public no-arg constructor.</strong><br><br><strong>Modern alternative:</strong> Jackson, Protocol Buffers, or JSON serialization — avoid Java serialization for security reasons (deserialization gadgets)."},

  {q:"What is transient and volatile — when do you use each?",d:"medium",
   a:"<strong>transient:</strong> excludes a field from Java serialization.<br><pre>class Session implements Serializable {\n  private String userId;\n  private transient Socket connection; // not serializable, skip it\n}</pre>When deserializing, transient fields are set to their default value (null for objects, 0 for primitives). Reconstruct them manually in <code>readObject()</code> if needed.<br><br><strong>volatile:</strong> tells the JVM that a field may be modified by multiple threads — disables caching, ensures visibility.<br><pre>class Worker {\n  private volatile boolean stopRequested;\n\n  public void run() {\n    while (!stopRequested) { ... } // always reads fresh value\n  }\n\n  public void shutdown() { stopRequested = true; } // visible to run() immediately\n}</pre><br><strong>What volatile does NOT do:</strong> it does NOT provide atomicity for compound operations like <code>count++</code>. Use <code>AtomicInteger</code> or synchronization for that.<br><br><strong>When to use volatile:</strong> simple flags (shutdown signal, status), double-checked locking (with proper pattern). For complex logic, use proper synchronization or <code>java.util.concurrent</code> utilities."},

  {q:"What are the most important Java 11-17 features a senior dev should know?",d:"medium",
   a:"<strong>Java 11 (LTS):</strong><ul><li><code>var</code> in lambda parameters: <code>(var x, var y) -&gt; x + y</code></li><li>String methods: <code>isBlank()</code>, <code>lines()</code>, <code>strip()</code>, <code>repeat(n)</code></li><li>HttpClient API (standard): async, HTTP/2 support</li><li><code>Files.readString()</code> / <code>writeString()</code></li></ul><br><strong>Java 14:</strong><ul><li>Switch expressions (stable): <code>int x = switch(day) { case MON -> 1; ... }</code></li><li>Records (preview): <code>record Point(int x, int y) {}</code></li></ul><br><strong>Java 15:</strong><ul><li>Text blocks (stable): multi-line strings with <code>\"\"\" ... \"\"\"</code></li><li>Sealed classes (preview): restrict which classes can extend/implement</li></ul><br><strong>Java 16:</strong><ul><li>Pattern matching for <code>instanceof</code> (stable)</li><li>Records (stable)</li></ul><br><strong>Java 17 (LTS):</strong><ul><li>Sealed classes (stable): <code>sealed class Shape permits Circle, Square {}</code></li><li>Pattern matching for switch (preview)</li><li>Restored strong encapsulation of JDK internals (no more <code>--add-opens</code> workarounds)</li></ul><br><strong>For interviews:</strong> know <code>var</code>, records, text blocks, sealed classes, pattern matching for instanceof."},

  {q:"How does String.intern() vs String.valueOf() vs toString() differ?",d:"medium",
   a:"<strong>String.intern():</strong> returns the canonical representation from the <strong>String pool</strong>. If the pool already contains an equal string, returns that; otherwise, adds this string to the pool and returns it.<br><pre>String s1 = new String(\"hello\").intern();\nString s2 = \"hello\";\nSystem.out.println(s1 == s2); // true — both point to pooled \"hello\"</pre>Use case: deduplication when you have many repeated strings (e.g., parsing a large file with repeated tokens). Don't overuse — the pool is in native memory (PermGen in Java 7, heap in Java 8+).<br><br><strong>String.valueOf(obj):</strong> static method that converts an object to a String. If obj is null, returns <code>\"null\"</code> (does NOT throw NPE).<br><pre>String s = String.valueOf(null); // \"null\"\nString s = null.toString();      // NullPointerException!</pre>Internally: <code>obj == null ? \"null\" : obj.toString()</code>. Safe to use with nullable objects.<br><br><strong>toString():</strong> instance method on Object. Returns a string representation of the object. Default implementation: <code>ClassName@hashCode</code>. Most classes override it for meaningful output.<br><pre>new User(\"Alice\").toString(); // \"User(name=Alice)\" if overridden</pre><br><strong>Rule:</strong> use <code>String.valueOf()</code> when the object might be null; use <code>.toString()</code> when you know it's non-null."}
);